stamp";i:1404838980;s:6:"col_id";N;s:8:"col_name";N;s:16:"col_media_source";N;s:13:"col_home_page";N;s:13:"col_shorthand";N;s:26:"col_media_source_shorthand";N;s:27:"col_author_twitter_username";N;s:8:"col_tags";N;s:15:"col_description";N;s:23:"col_last_post_timestamp";N;}i:10;O:8:"stdClass":36:{s:7:"post_id";i:32460;s:8:"post_url";s:172:"http://ritachemaly.wordpress.com/2014/07/08/reclaiming-and-redefining-rights-icpd20-status-of-sexual-and-reproductive-health-and-rights-in-the-middle-east-and-north-africa/";s:10:"post_title";s:123:"Reclaiming and Redefining Rights: ICPD+20: Status of Sexual and Reproductive Health and Rights in the Middle East and No...";s:10:"post_image";s:0:"";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:123:"The year 2014 was meant to be the year that ended the Program of Action adopted by the Cairo Conference for Population a...";s:7:"blog_id";s:11:"ritachemaly";s:14:"post_timestamp";i:1404830760;s:12:"post_content";s:510:"The year 2014 was meant to be the year that ended the Program of Action adopted by the Cairo Conference for Population and Development (ICPD) in 1994. The document was a paradigm shift in understanding and framing reproductive health and rights and prioritizing individuals’ rights to choose and make decisions with regards to their own […]<img alt="" border="0" src="http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=ritachemaly.wordpress.com&blog=7747045&post=5153&subd=ritachemaly&ref=&feed=1" width="1" height="1">";s:17:"post_image_height";i:0;s:16:"post_image_width";i:0;s:11:"post_visits";i:2;s:18:"post_twitterShares";i:1;s:19:"post_facebookShares";i:1;s:16:"post_totalShares";i:2;s:16:"post_socialScore";i:5;s:13:"post_virality";i:6;s:9:"blog_name";s:19:"Rita Chemaly's Blog";s:16:"blog_description";s:51:"Political and Social activism in Lebanon and Abroad";s:8:"blog_url";s:32:"http://ritachemaly.wordpress.com";s:11:"blog_author";s:12:"Rita Chemaly";s:28:"blog_author_twitter_username";s:11:"Ritachemaly";s:13:"blog_rss_feed";s:38:"http://ritachemaly.wordpress.com/feed/";s:9:"blog_tags";s:19:"activism , politics";s:2:"id";i:120;s:11:"blog_active";i:1;s:24:"blog_last_post_timestamp";i:1404979440;s:6:"col_id";N;s:8:"col_name";N;s:16:"col_media_source";N;s:13:"col_home_page";N;s:13:"col_shorthand";N;s:26:"col_media_source_shorthand";N;s:27:"col_author_twitter_username";N;s:8:"col_tags";N;s:15:"col_description";N;s:23:"col_last_post_timestamp";N;}i:11;O:8:"stdClass":36:{s:7:"post_id";i:32464;s:8:"post_url";s:111:"http://khaledalameddine.wordpress.com/2014/07/08/hezbollahs-pre-schoolers-guide-to-war-a-peek-inside-mahdi-mag/";s:10:"post_title";s:68:"Hezbollah’s Pre-Schooler’s Guide to War: A Peek Inside Mahdi Mag";s:10:"post_image";s:71:"http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151322.jpg";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:123:"Being a librarian, I am exposed to published atrocities almost every single day. From the most pointless tabloids to tit...";s:7:"blog_id";s:16:"khaledalameddine";s:14:"post_timestamp";i:1404817200;s:12:"post_content";s:9138:"<p>Being a librarian, I am exposed to published atrocities almost every single day. From the most pointless tabloids to titles such as “50 Words You Need to Know to Sound Smart.” Yet, July 7th brought with it the most despicable print I have seen since reading a few pages from Mein Kampf. Below are the pictures I took of my first encounter with Mahdi Magazine with commentary; because well, I can’t “resist” commenting.</p>
<p><a href="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151322.jpg"><img src="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151322.jpg?w=225&h=300" alt="20140707_151322" width="225" height="300"></a></p>
<p>Mahdi is a monthly magazine published by the Hezbollah-affiliated Mahdi Scouts. The above cover is that of its 7th issue; as it says on the cover, it is made for preschoolers aged 4-7. Right from the title are the words “<em>Ana ‘Uqawim”</em> or I resist; and they’re not talking about resisting the urge of playing candy crush over studying or whatever a preschooler magazine usually preaches. No, they’re talking about “resisting the enemy.”</p>
<p><a href="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151332.jpg"><img src="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151332.jpg?w=225&h=300" alt="20140707_151332" width="225" height="300"></a></p>
<p>The magazine begins with a small introduction targeting parents and aiding them in teaching their children “the idea of resistance;” suggesting a metaphor which includes building a house where people live  peacefully and happily guarded by a resistance militant and his friends. The magazine then mentions how children at this age begin to understand “virtuous” principles and that the idea of the resistance will clarify the meaning of the nation and why the child should love it. </p>
<p>So according to Mahdi Mag, the nation’s meaning (and why we should love it) is related to their support of the resistance. Indirect propaganda message: The reason behind your nationalism should be the love of the resistance.</p>
<p><a href="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151339.jpg"><img src="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151339.jpg?w=225&h=300" alt="20140707_151339" width="225" height="300"></a></p>
<p>A children’s rhyme about defending your land, victory and how the enemy will reap defeat; nothing out of the ordinary for a preschooler. More confusing is the picture on this page, a kid dressed in military uniform, standing on a tank with a pigeon on it, giving flowers to fellow children… Is this supposed to be cute or something?</p>
<p><a href="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151352.jpg"><img src="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151352.jpg?w=225&h=300" alt="20140707_151352" width="225" height="300"></a></p>
<p>Now we finally get to the fun parts. Everyone knows kids love to color, they also tend to get a special thrill from coloring military equipment (note the sectarian inclusion of a Qur’an.) Mahdi Mag also tests your child’s logic through a grenade/assault rifle pattern exercise decorated with some barbed wire for your child’s visual comfort.</p>
<p><a href="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151406.jpg"><img src="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151406.jpg?w=225&h=300" alt="20140707_151406" width="225" height="300"></a></p>
<p>Help the bunny cross the minefield then practice your mathematical skills by counting and distinguishing landmines! I have to admit though, a maze has never been this thrilling. Of course, Mahdi Mag didn’t miss the chance of reminding the reader about the occupation and how it planted landmines in our fields while they’re at it.</p>
<p><a href="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151420.jpg"><img src="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151420.jpg?w=225&h=300" alt="20140707_151420" width="225" height="300"></a></p>
<p>Kids also adore stickers; Mahdi guarantees these stickers are lethally fun.</p>
<p><a href="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151426.jpg"><img src="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151426.jpg?w=225&h=300" alt="20140707_151426" width="225" height="300"></a></p>
<p>More coloring fun. This time of an curiously young fighter praying near the front line. Note the Turbah (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turbah" rel="nofollow">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turbah</a>) on the praying mat, another hint about the sect of the revered resistance militant described in the magazine.</p>
<p><a href="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151433.jpg"><img src="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151433.jpg?w=225&h=300" alt="20140707_151433" width="225" height="300"></a></p>
<p>Another maze, this time to assist the (very young) militant to lift the yellow flag over the enemy bunker.</p>
<p><a href="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151509.jpg"><img src="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151509.jpg?w=225&h=300" alt="20140707_151509" width="225" height="300"></a></p>
<p>A poem addressed to “my father the martyr.” A pretty dark theme for a preschooler who is (hopefully) yet to be faced with death or to fully capable of understanding it.</p>
<p><a href="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151517.jpg"><img src="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151517.jpg?w=225&h=300" alt="20140707_151517" width="225" height="300"></a></p>
<p><a href="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151524.jpg"><img src="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151524.jpg?w=225&h=300" alt="20140707_151524" width="225" height="300"></a></p>
<p>A short story about the 2000 and the 2006 wars. It’s literary merit lies in how it portrays war crafts, destruction and victory in a “cute” frame. I hope the sarcasm is clear enough.</p>
<p><a href="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151442.jpg"><img src="http://khaledalameddine.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/20140707_151442.jpg?w=225&h=300" alt="20140707_151442" width="225" height="300"></a></p>
<p>The magazine comes with a pull-out you can send to it; the required spaces include writing what the child understood from the issue, what rhymes did he/she memorize and imagining a story about the resistance.</p>
<p>I cannot begin to describe how despicable this piece of propaganda is. The fact that it targets preschoolers; children who are still learning how to read and write, is unsettling. Even The Hitler Youth respected childhood enough to publish magazines targeting teenagers rather than children (Der Pimpf.) Moreover, the magazine plasters a sectarian identity to the hero it describes, the resistance militant and covers almost every woman with the veil to set another standard for the supporters of the resistance.</p>
<p>The danger of indoctrinating children in this manner goes far beyond the already abhorrent aim of preparing preschoolers for a battle; the real danger lies in the standard the magazine sets. Children accept whatever information they are told as truths, truths they continue to uphold a large number of even when they become adults. Childhood-learned myths are anchored even in the brightest of minds until the myths are disproved. Until a few years ago, I thought whiskey is made from fermented onion juice because of a joke my brother ran on me when I was a kid, for example. The goal is to establish the glory of the resistance in the minds of future adults; it would be then easy to discredit and defame anyone only for opposing the benevolent resistance and “siding with the despised enemy.” A lot more can be said about the harm such a publication can do; but I think it’s obvious enough</p>
<p>Historian Orlando Figes quoted an unnamed Soviet schooling theorist:</p>
<p>“We must make the young into a generation of Communists. Children, like soft wax, are very malleable and they should be molded into good Communists… We must rescue children from the harmful influence of the family… We must nationalize them. From the earliest days of their little lives, they must find themselves under the beneficent influence of Communist schools… To oblige the mother to give her child to the Soviet state – that is our task.”</p>
<p>By glorifying the militant and portraying fighting the enemy as the ultimate ambition, it seems like Hezbollah is trying to apply the same sinister agenda.</p><br><a rel="nofollow" href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/khaledalameddine.wordpress.com/42/"><img alt="" border="0" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/khaledalameddine.wordpress.com/42/"></a> <img alt="" border="0" src="http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=khaledalameddine.wordpress.com&blog=63433787&post=42&subd=khaledalameddine&ref=&feed=1" width="1" height="1">";s:17:"post_image_height";i:2560;s:16:"post_image_width";i:1920;s:11:"post_visits";i:14;s:18:"post_twitterShares";i:5;s:19:"post_facebookShares";i:20;s:16:"post_totalShares";i:25;s:16:"post_socialScore";i:27;s:13:"post_virality";i:26;s:9:"blog_name";s:17:"Khaled Alameddine";s:16:"blog_description";s:23:"Sharing a few thoughts.";s:8:"blog_url";s:38:"http://khaledalameddine.wordpress.com/";s:11:"blog_author";s:17:"Khaled Alameddine";s:28:"blog_author_twitter_username";s:9:"KhaledA93";s:13:"blog_rss_feed";s:43:"http://khaledalameddine.wordpress.com/feed/";s:9:"blog_tags";s:8:"politics";s:2:"id";i:263;s:11:"blog_active";i:1;s:24:"blog_last_post_timestamp";i:1404817200;s:6:"col_id";N;s:8:"col_name";N;s:16:"col_media_source";N;s:13:"col_home_page";N;s:13:"col_shorthand";N;s:26:"col_media_source_shorthand";N;s:27:"col_author_twitter_username";N;s:8:"col_tags";N;s:15:"col_description";N;s:23:"col_last_post_timestamp";N;}i:12;O:8:"stdClass":36:{s:7:"post_id";i:32453;s:8:"post_url";s:79:"https://now.mmedia.me/lb/en/newsandpolitics/554844-why-baghdadi-talks-like-that";s:10:"post_title";s:28:"Why Baghdadi talks like that";s:10:"post_image";s:124:"http://now.mmedia.me/Pages/ImageStreamer/param/MediaThumbID__11be43ee-3f16-4302-88e8-12a438ac25e6/w__616/h__394/baghdadi.jpg";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:126:"Caliph Ibrahim thinks speaking in the style of Quran recitation makes him more holy. Some Islamic scholars vehemently disagree";s:7:"blog_id";N;s:14:"post_timestamp";i:1404814588;s:12:"post_content";s:3079:"<p>There are a great many oddities with the speech last Friday by ISIS/IS leader Ibrahim Awad Ibrahim al-Badri (aka Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi, aka &ldquo;Caliph Ibrahim&rdquo;), and while many have been amused by his apparently expensive wristwatch, I am myself less inclined to be surprised at a religious megalomaniac indulging the perks of power.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>No, for me the weirdest aspect is the way the guy spoke; abruptly elongating various vowels and consonants in a manner that totally disrupts natural oratory rhythm. If one knew no better, one would think he suffered from a stutter or other speech impediment, if not indeed something worse.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>But in fact what he&rsquo;s doing &ndash; which is something new, not practiced by the likes of Bin Laden or Zawahiri &ndash; is speaking in accordance with the Islamic rules of reciting the Quran, known as tajweed (literally &ldquo;improvement&rdquo;). The madd (&ldquo;extension&rdquo;) convention, for example, mandates doubling the length of a long vowel if it is preceded by a short vowel (haraka). In addition to tajweed, Quran recitation techniques follow one of at least seven styles (qira&rsquo;at), each having, according to one Islamic blog, its own &ldquo;unique mood, flourishes, tempo, pitch, vocal &lsquo;color&rsquo; and durations of certain notes and pauses.&rdquo; I&rsquo;m unable to ascertain exactly which qira&rsquo;a Baghdadi adheres to, but it&rsquo;s safe to assume he&rsquo;s done some hard thinking on it, and can argue with conviction why it is the correct one (to recite the Quran improperly, after all, constitutes the sin of lahn, which another website informs us &ldquo;may deprive the reader of any reward in the Hereafter&rdquo;).</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Then again, perhaps Baghdadi needs to brush up on his theory, because according to this website, &ldquo;It is not permissible to apply the rules of tajweed [&hellip;] to normal conversation. The majority of the scholars are of the view that the rules of tajweed apply only to the words of the Quran.&rdquo;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Worse, another website says some clerics go so far as to consider the use of tajweed for non-Quranic recital as tantamount to the grave sin of bid&rsquo;a (&ldquo;innovation&rdquo;), on the grounds that it might lead listeners to confuse the speaker&rsquo;s own words with those of Allah.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Come to think of it, for the man declaring himself the absolute ruler of every Muslim on earth, the comparison may not necessarily be an unwelcome one.</p><p>                                      ISIS leader and new global caliph appears in first-ever video speech on Friday, July 4, 2014                                   </p><p>                                      Perhaps Baghdadi needs to brush up on his theory, because according to this website, “It is not permissible to apply the rules of tajweed […] to normal conversation. The majority of the scholars are of the view that the rules of tajweed apply only to the words of the Quran.”                                   </p>";s:17:"post_image_height";i:394;s:16:"post_image_width";i:616;s:11:"post_visits";i:26;s:18:"post_twitterShares";i:18;s:19:"post_facebookShares";i:1;s:16:"post_totalShares";i:19;s:16:"post_socialScore";i:38;s:13:"post_virality";i:24;s:9:"blog_name";N;s:16:"blog_description";N;s:8:"blog_url";N;s:11:"blog_author";N;s:28:"blog_author_twitter_username";N;s:13:"blog_rss_feed";N;s:9:"blog_tags";N;s:2:"id";N;s:11:"blog_active";N;s:24:"blog_last_post_timestamp";N;s:6:"col_id";i:9;s:8:"col_name";s:22:"Alex Rowell (NOW Blog)";s:16:"col_media_source";s:17:"Now Lebanon Blogs";s:13:"col_home_page";s:46:"https://now.mmedia.me/lb/en/Author/Alex.Rowell";s:13:"col_shorthand";s:14:"alexrowell-now";s:26:"col_media_source_shorthand";s:11:"now_lebanon";s:27:"col_author_twitter_username";s:13:"disgraceofgod";s:8:"col_tags";s:8:"politics";s:15:"col_description";s:151:"Alex Rowell joined NOW in Beirut as a reporter and blogger in February 2012. A British citizen, he was raised in Dubai and studied economics in London.";s:23:"col_last_post_timestamp";i:1404814588;}i:13;O:8:"stdClass":36:{s:7:"post_id";i:32424;s:8:"post_url";s:81:"http://www.beirutreport.com/2014/07/whitewashing-continues-at-new-york-times.html";s:10:"post_title";s:40:"Whitewashing continues at New York Times";s:10:"post_image";s:121:"http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-Gz0FTgxjpy4/U7rbDyf8TLI/AAAAAAAAJSA/lpffSC-P4zg/s1600/Screen+Shot+2014-07-07+at+12.36.31+PM.png";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:123:"Violence toward Palestinians continues to be downplayed or completely omitted by "The Paper of Record," i.e. The New Yor...";s:7:"blog_id";s:12:"beirutreport";s:14:"post_timestamp";i:1404763620;s:12:"post_content";s:6284:"<div dir="ltr" trbidi="on"><div><a href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-Gz0FTgxjpy4/U7rbDyf8TLI/AAAAAAAAJSA/lpffSC-P4zg/s1600/Screen+Shot+2014-07-07+at+12.36.31+PM.png" imageanchor="1"><img border="0" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-Gz0FTgxjpy4/U7rbDyf8TLI/AAAAAAAAJSA/lpffSC-P4zg/s1600/Screen+Shot+2014-07-07+at+12.36.31+PM.png" height="178" width="640"></a></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>Violence toward Palestinians continues to be downplayed or completely omitted by "The Paper of Record," i.e. The New York Times. </div><div><br></div><div>Yesterday, I reported how dead Palestinians have <a href="http://www.beirutreport.com/2014/07/no-name-dead-palestinians.html" target="_blank">no names </a>in the Times' coverage, in contrast to dead Israelis who are described in personal, humanizing detail including ages, full names and schools they attended. </div><div><br></div><div>But today, the six dead Palestinians and 400 arrested, had <b>no mention at all</b> in a piece by the same author, Elizabeth Kershner. Instead we are vaguely told about "clashes" and "the killings on each sides" which dilutes any direct responsibility in the Palestinians deaths or arrests:  </div><div><br></div><div><a href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-S0Zmb9BYsK0/U7rm9TUPjaI/AAAAAAAAJSU/u3WEu0JpMmI/s1600/Screen+Shot+2014-07-07+at+1.13.47+PM.png" imageanchor="1"><img border="0" src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-S0Zmb9BYsK0/U7rm9TUPjaI/AAAAAAAAJSU/u3WEu0JpMmI/s1600/Screen+Shot+2014-07-07+at+1.13.47+PM.png" height="180" width="640"></a></div><div><br></div><div>Contrast this to the very specific naming of the killed Israelis once again today:</div><div><br></div><div><a href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-jKsBcPai9dQ/U7roAu6IaGI/AAAAAAAAJSg/5MQICXssnow/s1600/Screen+Shot+2014-07-07+at+1.13.10+PM.png" imageanchor="1"><img border="0" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-jKsBcPai9dQ/U7roAu6IaGI/AAAAAAAAJSg/5MQICXssnow/s1600/Screen+Shot+2014-07-07+at+1.13.10+PM.png" height="122" width="640"></a></div><div><br></div><div><b>Why does the Times have so much difficulty naming dead Palestinians? </b></div><div><br></div><div>Why do Palestinian deaths and arrests fade so quickly from the headlines, while Israelis ones remain, week after week?</div><div><br></div><div>We are told in a subsequent paragraph that "Hamas said seven of its militants were killed" but the paper does nothing to verify any details about these deaths, including the age of those killed or what they were doing at the time despite a total of five Times reporters working on this story. By simply identifying them as "militants" their deaths are made inconsequential. </div><div><br></div><div>Even worse is that the Times reporter downplays violent Israeli language, after a police spokesman shockingly calls the brutal murder of a 16 year old an act of "nationalism"</div><div><br></div><div>The reporter goes so far as to explain away the very violent language as a technical reference to a previous killing.</div><div><br></div><div><a href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-LOh87656n5M/U7rtqUk6xMI/AAAAAAAAJSw/qqs1nn-Z1KI/s1600/Screen+Shot+2014-07-07+at+1.10.46+PM.png" imageanchor="1"><img border="0" src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-LOh87656n5M/U7rtqUk6xMI/AAAAAAAAJSw/qqs1nn-Z1KI/s1600/Screen+Shot+2014-07-07+at+1.10.46+PM.png" height="202" width="640"></a></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><b>Can you imagine if a Palestinian police spokesperson called the killing of an Israeli child a "nationalistic" killing? Can you imagine the headlines and demonization that would generate? </b>One can even imagine talk of sanctions against the Palestinian government. </div><div><br></div><div>I wonder if Kershner would have explained it away. Would she have written that labelling the killing of a Jew "nationalistic" as an innocent reference to previous events?</div><div><br></div><div>Finally Kershner further whitewashes the idea that violence toward Palestinians could be widespread in Israeli society. Instead, again she invents a more innocent reference, calling Israeli violence marginal, part of a "nationalist fringe"</div><div><br></div><div><a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-nIBNDzLsgjw/U7rx8zX-vvI/AAAAAAAAJS8/PWWR4yu8eag/s1600/Screen+Shot+2014-07-07+at+12.28.33+PM.png" imageanchor="1"><img border="0" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-nIBNDzLsgjw/U7rx8zX-vvI/AAAAAAAAJS8/PWWR4yu8eag/s1600/Screen+Shot+2014-07-07+at+12.28.33+PM.png" height="164" width="640"></a></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>But as the writer Ali Abunimah pointed out, the violence toward Palestinians is not marginal in any sense but spoken loudly by members of the ruling party in Parliament who have incited hatred and legitimized killing. These include Knesset member <span><span>Ayelet Shaked who advocates <a href="http://electronicintifada.net/blogs/ali-abunimah/israeli-lawmakers-call-genocide-palestinians-gets-thousands-facebook-likes" target="_blank">war against "the entire Palestinian nation" including women and children, whom she references as "snakes."</a></span></span></div><div><span><span><br></span></span></div><div><span><span><span>Of course anyone who has studied the living conditions of Palestinians will know that violence is pervasive and daily under military rule, from the brutality of soldiers to armed </span></span><span><span>settlers to the speeches produced by the office of the Prime Minister, which trickles down to very popular hate pages in Israeli social media as also pointed out by Abunimah's <a href="http://electronicintifada.net/blogs/ali-abunimah/israeli-lawmakers-call-genocide-palestinians-gets-thousands-facebook-likes" target="_blank">work</a>.  </span></span></span></div><div><span><span><br></span></span></div><div><span><span><span>So how does the world's most famous newspaper pick its editors and reporters? Do they research the context of the countries they report on? Or does it pick the type of people who omit deaths based on ethnicity, fail to see a system of daily violence and injustice, explain away hate speech as marginal-- and worse still-- accept terms heard with their own ears from police spokespersons like "nationalistic murder." </span></span></span></div><div><span><span><span><br></span></span></span></div><div><br></div><br></div>";s:17:"post_image_height";i:305;s:16:"post_image_width";i:1094;s:11:"post_visits";i:25;s:18:"post_twitterShares";i:3;s:19:"post_facebookShares";i:3;s:16:"post_totalShares";i:6;s:16:"post_socialScore";i:32;s:13:"post_virality";i:14;s:9:"blog_name";s:17:"The Beirut Report";s:16:"blog_description";s:56:"An inside look at Lebanon, the Middle East and its media";s:8:"blog_url";s:23:"http://beirutreport.com";s:11:"blog_author";s:12:"Habib Battah";s:28:"blog_author_twitter_username";s:7:"habib_b";s:13:"blog_rss_feed";s:47:"http://www.beirutreport.com/feeds/posts/default";s:9:"blog_tags";s:17:"society, politics";s:2:"id";i:17;s:11:"blog_active";i:1;s:24:"blog_last_post_timestamp";i:1405268160;s:6:"col_id";N;s:8:"col_name";N;s:16:"col_media_source";N;s:13:"col_home_page";N;s:13:"col_shorthand";N;s:26:"col_media_source_shorthand";N;s:27:"col_author_twitter_username";N;s:8:"col_tags";N;s:15:"col_description";N;s:23:"col_last_post_timestamp";N;}i:14;O:8:"stdClass":36:{s:7:"post_id";i:32418;s:8:"post_url";s:78:"http://blog.octavianasr.com/2014/07/waiting-for-global-movement-of-change.html";s:10:"post_title";s:39:"Waiting for A Global Movement of Change";s:10:"post_image";s:0:"";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:123:"What if instead of celebrating independence or national day, and instead of military parades and proud displays of natio...";s:7:"blog_id";s:11:"octavianasr";s:14:"post_timestamp";i:1404753720;s:12:"post_content";s:390:"What if instead of celebrating independence or national day, and instead of military parades and proud displays of national colors on hats, shirts, bathing suits and flip flops, we pause and reflect on whether we are actually where we need to be in this world and the best ways to preserve our freedom and wellbeing?

What if instead of barbecues and fireworks, we observe the importance of";s:17:"post_image_height";i:0;s:16:"post_image_width";i:0;s:11:"post_visits";i:5;s:18:"post_twitterShares";i:6;s:19:"post_facebookShares";i:5;s:16:"post_totalShares";i:11;s:16:"post_socialScore";i:15;s:13:"post_virality";i:19;s:9:"blog_name";s:19:"Octavia Nasr's Blog";s:16:"blog_description";s:125:"In my pockets.. Memories and momentum.. Of life lived and moments cherished.. Like a child.. I'm always ready for a surprise!";s:8:"blog_url";s:27:"http://blog.octavianasr.com";s:11:"blog_author";s:12:"Octavia Nasr";s:28:"blog_author_twitter_username";s:11:"octavianasr";s:13:"blog_rss_feed";s:47:"http://blog.octavianasr.com/feeds/posts/default";s:9:"blog_tags";s:20:"politics, columnists";s:2:"id";i:103;s:11:"blog_active";i:1;s:24:"blog_last_post_timestamp";i:1404753720;s:6:"col_id";N;s:8:"col_name";N;s:16:"col_media_source";N;s:13:"col_home_page";N;s:13:"col_shorthand";N;s:26:"col_media_source_shorthand";N;s:27:"col_author_twitter_username";N;s:8:"col_tags";N;s:15:"col_description";N;s:23:"col_last_post_timestamp";N;}i:15;O:8:"stdClass":36:{s:7:"post_id";i:32416;s:8:"post_url";s:64:"https://now.mmedia.me/lb/en/lebanon/554757-a-big-medical-problem";s:10:"post_title";s:21:"A big medical problem";s:10:"post_image";s:126:"http://now.mmedia.me/Pages/ImageStreamer/param/MediaID__9e3ef506-6f00-4e94-aeff-ab0ac888602a/w__616/h__394/1474906_1015169.jpg";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:66:"Politicians accuse Syrian doctors of working illegally in Lebanon.";s:7:"blog_id";N;s:14:"post_timestamp";i:1404749823;s:12:"post_content";s:3116:"<p>The head of the parliamentary health committee, MP Atef Majdalani, has a big-big problem with Syrian doctors working &ndash; OMG! &ndash; illegally in Lebanese hospitals and clinics in the eastern Bekaa Valley. The MP urged the Lebanese Order of Physicians to defend the rights of Lebanese doctor.</p><p>
Health Minister Wael Abou Faour tried to set things straight, by telling An Nahar newspaper that Syrian doctors are indeed prohibited from practicing their profession in Lebanon. However, most Syrian doctors and nurses that reach Lebanon are usually volunteers, treating their compatriots for free. They don&rsquo;t have money to get treated in Lebanese hospitals anyway. Insurance doesn&rsquo;t cover their health care; the hospitals refuse to treat them. Women give birth in the streets because the Lebanese health system refuses to accept them...</p><p>
The Lebanese physicians have ever hardly been mistreated or struggled to find a job. I have never seen an unemployed physician in Lebanon. But I have seen physicians who left Lebanon or who wanted to leave Lebanon in order to work abroad. The reason was not because they felt the Syrians were taking over their jobs, but because Lebanon&rsquo;s flawed health and insurance system failed their aspirations for research, progress and proper services.</p><p>
Lebanese public hospitals struggle to pay their salaries. That&rsquo;s not because of the Syrian doctors volunteering in the tents of East Bekaa&rsquo;s refugee camps. It&rsquo;s because of political quarreling or negligence.</p><p>
There was not a Lebanese doctor who lost his/her job in an incredibly well equipped hospital in Lebanon because of a Syrian doctor who treats refugees for free. In fact, I have seen very few Lebanese physicians making the effort to travel to the East Bekaa and give a helping hand for free in the refugee communities. Sometimes even local residents, who are Lebanese, have to travel tens of miles from East Bekaa to reach the hospital in Chtoura to get treatment. There is no one there to treat them in their own village.</p><p>
It seems Lebanon has a shortage of medical personnel, a shortage of medical equipment, a shortage of money in the health care system, a huge fraud problem with the public insurance system, etc. It can&rsquo;t afford the healthcare for another million people.</p><p>
Until all these problems are solved, and at least the Lebanese patients are taken care of properly, the Syrian refugee doctors giving a hand and treating their own compatriots should be a blessing and they should at least get a big &ldquo;thank you.&rdquo;</p><p>                                      Syrian refugee camp in Arsal, East Bekaa, where refugees did not receive medical assistance.                                    </p><p>                                      Until all these problems are solved, and at least the Lebanese patients are taken care of properly, the Syrian refugee doctors giving a hand and treating their own compatriots should be a blessing and they should at least get a big “thank you.”                                   </p>";s:17:"post_image_height";i:394;s:16:"post_image_width";i:616;s:11:"post_visits";i:7;s:18:"post_twitterShares";i:11;s:19:"post_facebookShares";i:7;s:16:"post_totalShares";i:18;s:16:"post_socialScore";i:19;s:13:"post_virality";i:23;s:9:"blog_name";N;s:16:"blog_description";N;s:8:"blog_url";N;s:11:"blog_author";N;s:28:"blog_author_twitter_username";N;s:13:"blog_rss_feed";N;s:9:"blog_tags";N;s:2:"id";N;s:11:"blog_active";N;s:24:"blog_last_post_timestamp";N;s:6:"col_id";i:15;s:8:"col_name";s:25:"Ana Maria Luca (NOW Blog)";s:16:"col_media_source";s:11:"Now Lebanon";s:13:"col_home_page";s:48:"https://now.mmedia.me/lb/en/Author/Ana.MariaLuca";s:13:"col_shorthand";s:16:"anamarialuca-now";s:26:"col_media_source_shorthand";s:11:"now_lebanon";s:27:"col_author_twitter_username";s:7:"aml1609";s:8:"col_tags";s:8:"politics";s:15:"col_description";s:157:"Ana Maria has been reporting for NOW English since August 2009. She is an experienced journalist specialized in conflict reporting and international affairs.";s:23:"col_last_post_timestamp";i:1405012665;}i:16;O:8:"stdClass":36:{s:7:"post_id";i:32433;s:8:"post_url";s:89:"http://blogoftheboss.com/german-bride-vs-brazilian-groom-a-lebanese-match-made-in-heaven/";s:10:"post_title";s:74:"German Bride VS Brazilian Groom – A Lebanese “match” made in heaven!";s:10:"post_image";s:109:"http://blogoftheboss.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/wpid-10348215_10154314268400223_2490567349325968190_n.jpg";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:123:"When reknown entertainer Josiane el Zir and her soon to be husban Marwan Hatoum were planning their wedding, they had no...";s:7:"blog_id";s:13:"blogoftheboss";s:14:"post_timestamp";i:1404737220;s:12:"post_content";s:1216:"<p>When reknown entertainer <a href="http://twitter.com/josianeelzir">Josiane el Zir </a>and her soon to be husban Marwan Hatoum were planning their wedding, they had no clue their two favorite <strong>World Cup</strong> teams, <strong>Brazil and Germany</strong>, would be competing on the same day in Rio!</p>
<p>After the date of the match was set, Josiane launched an online voting on this funny wall photo which triggered a flow of Likes and Comments: <strong>The Bride vs The Groom! Who will you vote for?</strong></p>
<p><a href="http://blogoftheboss.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/wpid-10348215_10154314268400223_2490567349325968190_n.jpg"><img title="10348215_10154314268400223_2490567349325968190_n.jpg" alt="lebanon world cup funny josiane el zir brazil germany" src="http://blogoftheboss.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/wpid-10348215_10154314268400223_2490567349325968190_n.jpg"></a></p>
<p>This is just another funny way how the football fever made its way into our daily lives and became part of every moment we share online.</p>
<p>Until the church bells are ringing and the referee whistles are sounding, who will YOU vote for! <strong>Groom Vs Bride, pick your choice in the comment box!</strong></p>";s:17:"post_image_height";i:639;s:16:"post_image_width";i:960;s:11:"post_visits";i:14;s:18:"post_twitterShares";i:5;s:19:"post_facebookShares";i:69;s:16:"post_totalShares";i:74;s:16:"post_socialScore";i:31;s:13:"post_virality";i:34;s:9:"blog_name";s:16:"Blog of the Boss";s:16:"blog_description";s:68:"Strong believer in social change and in the healing power of comedy.";s:8:"blog_url";s:25:"http://blogoftheboss.com/";s:11:"blog_author";s:10:"Ralph Aoun";s:28:"blog_author_twitter_username";s:9:"ralphaoun";s:13:"blog_rss_feed";s:30:"http://blogoftheboss.com/feed/";s:9:"blog_tags";s:17:"politics, society";s:2:"id";i:287;s:11:"blog_active";i:1;s:24:"blog_last_post_timestamp";i:1404737220;s:6:"col_id";N;s:8:"col_name";N;s:16:"col_media_source";N;s:13:"col_home_page";N;s:13:"col_shorthand";N;s:26:"col_media_source_shorthand";N;s:27:"col_author_twitter_username";N;s:8:"col_tags";N;s:15:"col_description";N;s:23:"col_last_post_timestamp";N;}i:17;O:8:"stdClass":36:{s:7:"post_id";i:32402;s:8:"post_url";s:108:"http://www.thenational.ae/business/industry-insights/the-life/watching-world-cup-a-complex-affair-in-lebanon";s:10:"post_title";s:46:"Watching World Cup a complex affair in Lebanon";s:10:"post_image";N;s:12:"post_excerpt";s:234:"Energy minister Arthur Nazarian should not have insulted our intelligence last week by casually prefixing a statement on the situation by saying “until we get 24-hour electricity….”, as if Lebanon was experiencing a temporary...";s:7:"blog_id";N;s:14:"post_timestamp";i:1404727872;s:12:"post_content";s:4684:"<p>I have known Nabil since we were kids. In fact, I once, as kids do, or at least did, threw a stone, which accidentally glanced off his head. As you can imagine, he was none too impressed and that night, probably because I felt bad, I fessed up to my mortified father, who marched me round to Nabil&#x2019;s house to apologise.</p><p>It was a bad move. The next day, Nabil, who as kids do, had forgotten about the incident, told me that, instead of resolving the matter, his father later beat him for causing such a fuss.</p><p>Nabil and I still laugh about the incident and, though I doubt his late father&#x2019;s belt had anything to do with it, he is a very unflappable man. Until it comes to football, that is. Once every two years, come the Fifa World Cup and European Championships, Nabil becomes rabid in his support for Germany&#x2019;s national football team, and the prospect of his beloved mannschaft reaching yet another final on Sunday has left him positively foaming with excitement.</p><p>But Lebanon would not be Lebanon if there weren&#x2019;t an added smidgen of anxiety in all this. You see, at the best of times, our village gets its evening power from 6pm to midnight on alternate nights. The World Cup semi-finals are scheduled to start at 11pm, so Nabil, who doesn&#x2019;t have a generator, knows that unless Electricit&#xe9; du Liban is feeling generous, he will miss either the first or second half of the game with Brazil.</p><p>And EDL is not in a giving mood these days. The company has announced that it can no longer maintain it&#x2019;s &#x201c;regular&#x201d; service, which in real speak is 21 hours a day in Beirut and around 10 to 15 hours a day elsewhere, depending on where you live. It needs an extra US$266 million to meet the extra demand created by the 1.5 million extra people we have welcomed from Syria and all those new homes built across the country during a rampant construction boom.</p><p>So how are we coping? Well, those who have them are making do with generators, private or communal, which of course creates an extra financial burden to end users. Generators are also hardly environmentally friendly but, more worryingly, at the communal end of the market they have become a semi-legitimate sector in their own right. (Indeed, one wonders what will happen to these now powerful cartels if and when &#x2014; a very big &#x201c;if&#x201d; and an even bigger &#x201c;when&#x201d; &#x2014; the country does fix its chronic power problem.</p><p>But they needn&#x2019;t worry. The complacency of the state is staggering. The energy minister Arthur Nazarian, like his predecessors, is powerless to do anything meaningful, but he really shouldn&#x2019;t have insulted our intelligence last week by casually prefixing a statement on the situation by saying &#x201c;until we get 24-hour electricity&#x201d;, as if Lebanon was experiencing a temporary blip rather than a quarter-century stain of shame on successive corrupt and inept governments.</p><p>But back to the football. I wrote that at the start of Brazil 2014 many Lebanese, my buddy Nabil included, were faced with the prospect of not being able to watch any of it, unless they signed up for a package from Sama, a local satellite provider that had the local broadcast rights.</p><p>Then, at the eleventh hour, the telecoms minister Butros Harb announced that his ministry had set aside $3 million from mobile telecom revenues to pay Sama for the right to air the games on Tele Liban, our unfashionable and underfunded state-run TV channel. It was a deal that, we thought, ensured that anyone with a TV could watch the global tournament free of charge.</p><p>But the next thing we knew was that Sama was suing TL for showing the games without permission. So what was the $3m for? It turns out, from what most of us can gather, that it was to allow Sama to distribute the rights to the many &#x201c;grey&#x201d; market satellite providers that serve about 75 per cent of the homes in the country.</p><p>Or looked at another way, the state used its money to perpetuate the livelihoods of what are essentially pirate operations. Talal Makdessi, a former advertising honcho and the current director general of TL, saw the insanity of the deal and is currently daring Sama to do its worst.</p><p>Meanwhile, back in the village, Nabil in his usual relaxed way has rationalised that he can&#x2019;t change the madness that is Lebanon. He just wants to fire up his nightly shisha and watch a bit of football with his wife and kids. It&#x2019;s not a lot to ask.</p><p> </p><p>Michael Karam is a freelance journalist based in Beirut </p><p></p><p>Follow us on Twitter @Ind_Insights</p>";s:17:"post_image_height";i:0;s:16:"post_image_width";i:0;s:11:"post_visits";i:10;s:18:"post_twitterShares";i:3;s:19:"post_facebookShares";i:0;s:16:"post_totalShares";i:3;s:16:"post_socialScore";i:15;s:13:"post_virality";i:9;s:9:"blog_name";N;s:16:"blog_description";N;s:8:"blog_url";N;s:11:"blog_author";N;s:28:"blog_author_twitter_username";N;s:13:"blog_rss_feed";N;s:9:"blog_tags";N;s:2:"id";N;s:11:"blog_active";N;s:24:"blog_last_post_timestamp";N;s:6:"col_id";i:6;s:8:"col_name";s:29:"Michael Karam at The National";s:16:"col_media_source";s:12:"The National";s:13:"col_home_page";s:109:"http://www.thenational.ae/apps/pbcs.dll/search?q=*&NavigatorFilter=[Byline:Michael%20Karam]&BuildNavigators=1";s:13:"col_shorthand";s:8:"mkaramtn";s:26:"col_media_source_shorthand";s:12:"the_national";s:27:"col_author_twitter_username";s:15:"Lebanesewineman";s:8:"col_tags";s:20:"columnists, politics";s:15:"col_description";s:40:"Michael Karam is a writer and journalist";s:23:"col_last_post_timestamp";i:1404727872;}i:18;O:8:"stdClass":36:{s:7:"post_id";i:32399;s:8:"post_url";s:203:"http://lbcblogs.com/when-the-earth-shakes-in-lebanon-take-matters-into-your-own-hands/?utm_source=rss&amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;utm_campaign=when-the-earth-shakes-in-lebanon-take-matters-into-your-own-hands";s:10:"post_title";s:80:"CONTRIBUTION: When the earth shakes in Lebanon: take matters into your own hands";s:10:"post_image";s:0:"";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:118:"Images of devastation following the 1995 Kobe, Japan. Source: The Asahi Shimbun
“Lebanon has so many fault lines, it";s:7:"blog_id";s:8:"lbcblogs";s:14:"post_timestamp";i:1404723900;s:12:"post_content";s:5871:"<div><a href="http://lbcblogs.com/?feed-stats-url=aHR0cDovL2xiY2Jsb2dzLmNvbS93cC1jb250ZW50L3VwbG9hZHMvMjAxNC8wNy9Lb2JlLTE5OTUuanBn"><img src="http://lbcblogs.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Kobe-1995.jpg" alt="Images of devastation following the 1995 Kobe, Japan. Source: The Asahi Shimbun" width="243" height="375"></a><p>Images of devastation following the 1995 Kobe, Japan. Source: The Asahi Shimbun</p></div>
<p>“Lebanon has so many fault lines, it’s surprising there aren’t more earthquakes around here,” or “Back in the days, the first thing I’d do during an earthquake was take cover. Today, I run to Twitter. How lovely.” These are just some of the jokes that only I have made when tremors have hit Lebanon in the last couple of months. And if we want to be completely accurate, they have been tremors and not earthquakes (tremors usually indicate a lower intensity and level of damage from the shaking of the earth than an earthquake, when intensity and damage caused is much higher).  </p>
<p>But joke as much as we may, when the tremor hits and the earthquake starts wreaking havoc, there isn’t much to laugh about. This is especially true in Lebanon, where very few buildings and infrastructure is equipped with anti-seismic mechanisms, while preparedness of the general public and government planning/awareness campaigns is practically nonexistent. Please correct me if I’m wrong but the Bhannes Center for Seismic and Scientific Research appears solely as a reactive center announcing when tremors take place and their magnitude, while Lebanon’s National Council for Scientific Research (CNRS) does nothing but issue post-event press releases, and the last time I checked, was plagued by the same inefficiency and corruption almost every institution in the sphere of influence of Nabih Berri is characterized by. You may say Lebanon has more immediate dangers to take care of, true, but when the earth moves, there is nothing more immediate, nothing scarier, no political dialogue to handle it and when it stops moving, it is already too late to do anything about it…. </p>
<p>So, as we usually do, we take matters into our own hands. My humble experience emanates from having lived 11 years in two of the most seismically-active countries in the world. The first country had experienced a 7,8 degree earthquake 5 years before I arrived. The other experienced a 7,2 earthquake shortly after I arrived, while we were expecting “the big one” to hit anytime thereafter.  </p>
<p>We have enough to worry about as it is, so use your common sense and these simple tips to stay as safe as much as is humanly possible when a big earthquake hits (Source: widely available earthquake preparedness guidelines online and EyeontheEast.org. Comments are mine):</p>
<p>1.	Do not panic (at least try not to panic)</p>
<p>2.	If you are at home, stay home and take cover underneath a solid structure in case objects start falling from shelves. For goodness sake don’t take the elevator to go out onto the streets to start screaming and praying for mercy or stand beneath the electricity pole that could fall on your head (the only time electricity won’t fail you). Open your door to have a fast exit in case you need it. I wouldn’t know what to tell those living in old apartment buildings, which are completely unequipped to sustain earthquakes, use your common sense, you may want to get far and away from our house.  </p>
<p>3.	Have a small bag at home (“the earthquake kit”), fill it with canned foods, cash money, maybe a blanket, bottled water, candles, batteries, a flash light and a radio (don’t give me the excuse that you went through the civil war and it can’t get worse than that, just get a small bag and leave it somewhere accessible). You may also want to turn off the gas canister and electricity if we are talking about a seriously big quake here.</p>
<p>4.	Agree on a meeting point with your immediate family members in case you aren’t all at home. In countries with earthquake preparedness mechanisms, schools or big public facilities are usually the place to met. In Lebanon, you pick your own, but don’t choose the airport (you’ve seen worse than an earthquake, right?!).</p>
<p>5.	If you are driving, chances are you won’t feel the quake, but may notice it from the panic on the streets (some people will have disregarded point no. 1 and others can’t really help it). Don’t hit the gas pedal to get home, park on the side and stand somewhere safe (that is, not below something that may fall on your head, not below the electricity poles and not on the beach in case a tsunami hits and throws you all the way to the safe shores of Ayia Napa).</p>
<p>There is no harm in reading this and keeping it in mind. A war is one thing, but when the earth calls the shots, we are all defenseless. Let’s just hope these will only be things you read about and never have to put into practice…</p>
<p><em>Marina Chamma is a Beirut-based freelance writer and blogger at <a href="http://lbcblogs.com/?feed-stats-url=aHR0cDovL2V5ZW9udGhlZWFzdC5vcmcv" title='\"Eyeontheeast.org\"' target='\"_blank\"'>EyeontheEast.org</a>. She has been featured in a variety of online publications and is a regular contributor to Your Middle East. Marina holds a B.A. in Political Science from the American University of Beirut and an M.Sc. in International Political Economy from the London School of Economics. You can follow her on <a href="http://lbcblogs.com/?feed-stats-url=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmFjZWJvb2suY29tL2V5ZW9udGhlZWFzdD9mcmVmPXRz" title='\"Facebook\"' target='\"_blank\"'>Facebook</a> and <a href="http://lbcblogs.com/?feed-stats-url=aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9leWVvbnRoZWVhc3Q=" title='\"Twitter' target='\"_blank\"'>Twitter</a>.<br></em></p>
 <img src="http://lbcblogs.com/?feed-stats-post-id=2718" width="1" height="1">";s:17:"post_image_height";i:0;s:16:"post_image_width";i:0;s:11:"post_visits";i:5;s:18:"post_twitterShares";i:13;s:19:"post_facebookShares";i:29;s:16:"post_totalShares";i:42;s:16:"post_socialScore";i:20;s:13:"post_virality";i:30;s:9:"blog_name";s:27:"Lebanese Blogging Community";s:16:"blog_description";s:52:"News is Monologue, Contribute & Create the Dialogue.";s:8:"blog_url";s:19:"http://lbcblogs.com";s:11:"blog_author";s:14:"Nadine Mazloum";s:28:"blog_author_twitter_username";s:8:"LBCBlogs";s:13:"blog_rss_feed";s:25:"http://lbcblogs.com/feed/";s:9:"blog_tags";s:17:"society, politics";s:2:"id";i:69;s:11:"blog_active";i:1;s:24:"blog_last_post_timestamp";i:1405089960;s:6:"col_id";N;s:8:"col_name";N;s:16:"col_media_source";N;s:13:"col_home_page";N;s:13:"col_shorthand";N;s:26:"col_media_source_shorthand";N;s:27:"col_author_twitter_username";N;s:8:"col_tags";N;s:15:"col_description";N;s:23:"col_last_post_timestamp";N;}i:19;O:8:"stdClass":36:{s:7:"post_id";i:32391;s:8:"post_url";s:86:"http://blogoftheboss.com/5-national-issues-more-important-than-our-assholes-literally/";s:10:"post_title";s:62:"5 national issues more important than our assholes! Literally.";s:10:"post_image";s:72:"http://blogoftheboss.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/wpid-safe_image.jpeg";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:123:"They call it the “Shame Test”; a rectal examination that allows a judge to determine whether a person is gay through...";s:7:"blog_id";s:13:"blogoftheboss";s:14:"post_timestamp";i:1404717120;s:12:"post_content";s:3711:"<p>They call it the <strong>“Shame Test”</strong>; a rectal examination that allows a judge to determine whether a person is gay through an <strong>“official anal inspection”</strong> and which transforms the chart of Human Rights into nothing more than an ass wipe.<br><a href="http://blogoftheboss.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/wpid-safe_image.jpeg"><img title="safe_image.jpeg" alt="gay anal tests homosexuals shame lebanon beirut" src="http://blogoftheboss.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/wpid-safe_image.jpeg"></a> </p>
<p>In fact, despite instructions of former Change & Reform Minister of Justice Chakib Kortbawi as well as the Lebanese Order of Doctors against subjecting people to these unhumane tests, a recent <a href="http://legal-agenda.com/article.php?id=788&lang=ar">blog post by the Legal Agenda</a> followed by an <a href="http://youtu.be/jCasXpMDprs">investigation by LBCI </a>reported that some judge, some security official and some doctor decided otherwise.</p>
<p><a href="http://blogoftheboss.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/wpid-2014-07-07-02.24.16.png.png"><img title="2014-07-07 02.24.16.png" alt=" gay anal tests homosexuals shame lebanon beirut" src="http://blogoftheboss.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/wpid-2014-07-07-02.24.16.png.png"></a></p><center><em>Recent victim of the Rectal Shame Exams as reported by LBCI</em></center>
<p>Away from generalization and until strict measures are taken against the people behind the application of these disgraceful procedures, the Lebanese government is to blame for, <em>to say the least</em>, its clear <strong>lack of priorities</strong>!</p>
<p><a href="http://blogoftheboss.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/wpid-2014-07-07-02.39.00.png.png"><img title="2014-07-07 02.39.00.png" alt=" gay anal tests homosexuals shame lebanon beirut" src="http://blogoftheboss.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/wpid-2014-07-07-02.39.00.png.png"></a> </p>
<p>So for our government to take its head out of its ass and its nose out of our asses, we have decided to expose all assets and list the <strong>TOP 10 national issues</strong> which it should obviously reconsider as more important than our assholes:</p>
<p>1- The empty Presidencial seat in Baabda and the political system’s inabilty to elect a strong Presidential candidate to represent all the Lebanese <strong>is more important than our assholes.</strong></p>
<p>2- The 65 Billion Dollar public debt which is increasing exponentially with every passing year and which encurs a debt at birth for every Lebanese new born<strong> is more important than our assholes.</strong></p>
<p>3- The Syrian Refugees which already reached 1/3 of the Lebanese population with no official plan ahead for organizing their presence for their own wellbeing as well as that of the Lebanese people <strong>is more important than our assholes.</strong></p>
<p>4- The auto-renewing parliament which re-elected itself without going back to the people’s vote thus taking away one of the last remaining rights of Lebanese citizens <strong>is more important than our assholes.</strong></p>
<p>5- The ISIS (aka DA3ESH) terrorist organization threatening the Lebanese people of continuing its recurrent bloody explosive attacks as well as publicly declaring its intent to occupy Lebanon and put an end to freedom of belief <strong>is more important than our assholes.</strong></p>
<p>To avoid being a pain in the ass, we will restrict ourselves to only a Top 5 list despite the presence of <strong>100′s of national issues</strong> requiring urgent governmental attention, the leading of which being the strict protection of Human Rights and the freedom of speech, thought and sexuality of the Lebanese People.</p>";s:17:"post_image_height";i:245;s:16:"post_image_width";i:470;s:11:"post_visits";i:23;s:18:"post_twitterShares";i:22;s:19:"post_facebookShares";i:53;s:16:"post_totalShares";i:75;s:16:"post_socialScore";i:33;s:13:"post_virality";i:35;s:9:"blog_name";s:16:"Blog of the Boss";s:16:"blog_description";s:68:"Strong believer in social change and in the healing power of comedy.";s:8:"blog_url";s:25:"http://blogoftheboss.com/";s:11:"blog_author";s:10:"Ralph Aoun";s:28:"blog_author_twitter_username";s:9:"ralphaoun";s:13:"blog_rss_feed";s:30:"http://blogoftheboss.com/feed/";s:9:"blog_tags";s:17:"politics, society";s:2:"id";i:287;s:11:"blog_active";i:1;s:24:"blog_last_post_timestamp";i:1404737220;s:6:"col_id";N;s:8:"col_name";N;s:16:"col_media_source";N;s:13:"col_home_page";N;s:13:"col_shorthand";N;s:26:"col_media_source_shorthand";N;s:27:"col_author_twitter_username";N;s:8:"col_tags";N;s:15:"col_description";N;s:23:"col_last_post_timestamp";N;}}